'''Jonas Magnus Thern''' (born 20 March 1967 in [[Falk<U+00F6>ping]]) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[association football]] manager and former professional  player who played as a [[midfielder (football)|midfielder]].

==Player career==
=== Early career ===

Born and raised in the town of [[V<U+00E4>rnamo]] in southern central Sweden, Thern started his professional career in 1985 when he joined the classic Swedish club of [[Malm<U+00F6> FF]], where he stayed for four years, earning him two titles in the 1986 and 1988 [[Allsvenskan]]. In 1989, he won the [[Guldbollen]] as Sweden's Footballer of the Year.

=== In Europe ===

From there he moved to the continent to play for [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]. He was part of a successful group of Scandinavian players that played for Benfica at the time, composed of Danish international [[Michael Manniche]] (1983<U+2013>1987), and the Swedish "armada" ; [[Mats Magnusson]] (1987<U+2013>1992), Thern (1989<U+2013>1992), [[Glenn Str<U+00F6>mberg]] (1982<U+2013>84) and [[Stefan Schwarz]] (1990<U+2013>1994) alongside coach [[Sven-G<U+00F6>ran Eriksson]] (1982<U+2013>1984 and 1989<U+2013>1992).

Thern went on to play for [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] (1992<U+2013>94), [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] (1994<U+2013>97) and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (1997<U+2013>99), but his career was cut short by injuries.

== International career ==

For [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], he played in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] and [[1992 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 92]], and then won the bronze medal in the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] in the U.S. Thern also competed for Sweden at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sports Reference|title=Jonas Thern Biography and Statistics|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/th/jonas-thern-1.html|accessdate=2009-10-28}}</ref>

Thern was the Sweden captain for seven years, between 1990 and 1997.

== Coaching career ==

After he retired as a player he become head coach for [[IFK V<U+00E4>rnamo]] between 2000 and 2001 and [[Halmstads BK]] 2001<U+2013>2003.

He has also worked as a [[sports commentator]] and as a teacher.

== Personal life ==
Jonas has a son, [[Simon Thern|Simon]], who is also a footballer currently playing for Malm<U+00F6> FF.

== Honours and awards ==

; Malmo FF:
* [[Allsvenskan]]: Winner (1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989)
* [[Allsvenskan play-offs|Allsvenskan play-off]]: Winner (1986, 1988)

* [[Svenska Cupen]]: Winner (1986, 1988)
; S.L. Benfica:
* [[Portuguese Liga]]: Winner (1990<U+2013>91)
* [[Portuguese SuperCup]]: Winner (1989)
; Sweden:
* [[FIFA World Cup]]: Third place (1994)
; Individual:
* [[Guldbollen]] (Golden Ball): Winner, Best Swedish Player (1989)

